		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Pimsleur language learning system</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>The <b>Pimsleur language learning system</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Language_acquisition" title="Language acquisition">language acquisition</a> method developed by <a href="/wiki/Paul_Pimsleur" title="Paul Pimsleur">Paul Pimsleur</a>. The system is based on four main ideas: anticipation, <a href="/wiki/Graduated_interval_recall" title="Graduated interval recall">graduated interval recall</a>, core vocabulary, and organic learning.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The Pimsleur method is an audio-based system, in which the listener constructs phrases or repeats from memory along with a recording. The system, as currently packaged by <a href="/wiki/Simon_%26_Schuster" title="Simon &amp; Schuster">Simon &amp; Schuster</a>, is made up of multiple thirty-minute lessons, which are repeated until 80% comprehension is attained, at which point the user may advance to the next lesson. Because the lessons repeat themselves and add new material<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_0-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>, they do not demand 100% mastery before moving on.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
